The Dynamics of Viral Marketing ∗ 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:We present an analysis of a person to person recommendation network, consisting of 4 million people who made 16 million recommendations on half a million products .
1-2:We observe the propagation of recommendations and the cascade sizes, which we explain by a simple stochastic model .
1-3:We then establish how the recommendation network grows over time and how effective it is from the viewpoint of the sender and receiver of the recommendations .
1-4:While on average recommendations are not very effective at inducing purchases and do not spread very far, we present a model that successfully identifies product and pricing categories for which viral marketing seems to be very effective .
1-5:J.4 [Social and Behavioral Sciences]: Economics .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:With consumers showing increasing resistance to traditional forms of advertising such as TV or newspaper ads, marketers have turned to alternate strategies, including viral marketing .
2-2:Viral marketing exploits existing social networks by encouraging customers to share product information with their friends .
2-3:Previously, a few in depth studies have shown that social networks affect the adoption of individual innovations and products (for a review see [15] or [16]) .
2-4:But until recently it has been difficult to measure how influential person to person recommendations actually are over a wide range of products .
2-5:We were able to directly measure and model the effectiveness of recommendations by studying one online retailer"s incentivised viral marketing program .
2-6:The website gave discounts to customers recommending any of its products to others, and then tracked the resulting purchases and additional recommendations .
2-7:Although word of mouth can be a powerful factor influencing purchasing decisions, it can be tricky for advertisers to tap into .
2-8:Some services used by individuals to communicate are natural candidates for viral marketing, because the product can be observed or advertised as part of the communication .
2-9:Email services such as Hotmail and Yahoo had very fast adoption curves because every email sent through them contained an advertisement for the service and because they were free .
2-10:Hotmail spent a mere $50,000 on traditional marketing and still grew from zero to 12 million users in 18 months [7] .
2-11:Google"s Gmail captured a significant part of market share in spite of the fact that the only way to sign up for the service was through a referral .
2-12:Most products cannot be advertised in such a direct way .
2-13:At the same time the choice of products available to consumers has increased manyfold thanks to online retailers who can supply a much wider variety of products than traditional brick and mortar stores .
2-14:Not only is the variety of products larger, but one observes a ‘fat tail" phenomenon, where a large fraction of purchases are of relatively obscure items .
2-15:On Amazon.com, somewhere between 20 to 40 percent of unit sales fall outside of its top 100,000 ranked products [2] .
2-16:Rhapsody, a streaming music service, streams more tracks outside than inside its top 10,000 tunes [1] .
2-17:Effectively advertising these niche products using traditional advertising approaches is impractical .
2-18:Therefore using more targeted marketing approaches is advantageous both to the merchant and the consumer, who would benefit from learning about new products .
2-19:The problem is partly addressed by the advent of online product and merchant reviews, both at retail sites such as EBay and Amazon, and specialized product comparison sites such as Epinions and CNET .
2-20:Quantitative marketing techniques have been proposed [12], and the rating of products and merchants has been shown to effect the likelihood of an item being bought [13, 4] .
2-21:Of further help to the consumer are collaborative filtering recommendations of the form people who bought x also bought y feature [11] .
2-22:These refinements help consumers discover new products 228 and receive more accurate evaluations, but they cannot completely substitute personalized recommendations that one receives from a friend or relative .
2-23:It is human nature to be more interested in what a friend buys than what an anonymous person buys, to be more likely to trust their opinion, and to be more influenced by their actions .
2-24:Our friends are also acquainted with our needs and tastes, and can make appropriate recommendations .
2-25:A Lucid Marketing survey found that 68% of individuals consulted friends and relatives before purchasing home electronics more than the half who used search engines to find product information [3] .
2-26:Several studies have attempted to model just this kind of network influence .
2-27:Richardson and Domingos [14] used Epinions" trusted reviewer network to construct an algorithm to maximize viral marketing efficiency assuming that individuals" probability of purchasing a product depends on the opinions on the trusted peers in their network .
2-28:Kempe, Kleinberg and Tardos [8] evaluate the efficiency of several algorithms for maximizing the size of influence set given various models of adoption .
2-29:While these models address the question of maximizing the spread of influence in a network, they are based on assumed rather than measured influence effects .
2-30:In contrast, in our study we are able to directly observe the effectiveness of person to person word of mouth advertising for hundreds of thousands of products for the first time .
2-31:We find that most recommendation chains do not grow very large, often terminating with the initial purchase of a product .
2-32:However, occasionally a product will propagate through a very active recommendation network .
2-33:We propose a simple stochastic model that seems to explain the propagation of recommendations .
2-34:Moreover, the characteristics of recommendation networks influence the purchase patterns of their members .
2-35:For example, individuals" likelihood of purchasing a product initially increases as they receive additional recommendations for it, but a saturation point is quickly reached .
2-36:Interestingly, as more recommendations are sent between the same two individuals, the likelihood that they will be heeded decreases .
2-37:We also propose models to identify products for which viral marketing is effective: We find that the category and price of product plays a role, with recommendations of expensive products of interest to small, well connected communities resulting in a purchase more often .
2-38:We also observe patterns in the timing of recommendations and purchases corresponding to times of day when people are likely to be shopping online or reading email .
2-39:We report on these and other findings in the following sections. .
3 THE RECOMMENDATION NETWORK :
3-1:2.1 Dataset description Our analysis focuses on the recommendation referral program run by a large retailer .
3-2:The program rules were as follows .
3-3:Each time a person purchases a book, music, or a movie he or she is given the option of sending emails recommending the item to friends .
3-4:The first person to purchase the same item through a referral link in the email gets a 10% discount .
3-5:When this happens the sender of the recommendation receives a 10% credit on their purchase .
3-6:The recommendation dataset consists of 15,646,121 recommendations made among 3,943,084 distinct users .
3-7:The data was collected from June 5 2001 to May 16 2003 .
3-8:In total, 548,523 products were recommended, 99% of them belonging to 4 main product groups: Books, DVDs, Music and Videos .
3-9:In addition to recommendation data, we also crawled the retailer"s website to obtain product categories, reviews and ratings for all products .
3-10:Of the products in our data set, 5813 (1%) were discontinued (the retailer no longer provided any information about them) .
3-11:Although the data gives us a detailed and accurate view of recommendation dynamics, it does have its limitations .
3-12:The only indication of the success of a recommendation is the observation of the recipient purchasing the product through the same vendor .
3-13:We have no way of knowing if the person had decided instead to purchase elsewhere, borrow, or otherwise obtain the product .
3-14:The delivery of the recommendation is also somewhat different from one person simply telling another about a product they enjoy, possibly in the context of a broader discussion of similar products .
3-15:The recommendation is received as a form email including information about the discount program .
3-16:Someone reading the email might consider it spam, or at least deem it less important than a recommendation given in the context of a conversation .
3-17:The recipient may also doubt whether the friend is recommending the product because they think the recipient might enjoy it, or are simply trying to get a discount for themselves .
3-18:Finally, because the recommendation takes place before the recommender receives the product, it might not be based on a direct observation of the product .
3-19:Nevertheless, we believe that these recommendation networks are reflective of the nature of word of mouth advertising, and give us key insights into the influence of social networks on purchasing decisions .
3-20:2.2 Recommendation network statistics For each recommendation, the dataset included the product and product price, sender ID, receiver ID, the sent date, and a buy bit, indicating whether the recommendation resulted in a purchase and discount .
3-21:The sender and receiver ID"s were shadowed .
3-22:We represent this data set as a directed multi graph .
3-23:The nodes represent customers, and a directed edge contains all the information about the recommendation .
3-24:The edge (i, j, p, t) indicates that i recommended product p to customer j at time t .
3-25:The typical process generating edges in the recommendation network is as follows: a node i first buys a product p at time t and then it recommends it to nodes j1, .
