6-6:more or less influential than a recommendation for a technical book, which may be made by a colleague at work or school .
6-7:Table 2 shows recommendation trends for all top level book categories by subject .
6-8:An analysis of other product types can be found in the extended version of the paper .
6-9:For clarity, we group the results by 4 different category types: fiction, personal leisure, professional technical, and nonfiction other .
6-10:Fiction encompasses categories such as Sci Fi and Romance, as well as children"s and young adult books .
6-11:Personal Leisure encompasses everything from gardening, photography and cooking to health and religion .
6-12:First, we compare the relative number of recommendations to reviews posted on the site (column cav rp1 of table 2) .
6-13:Surprisingly, we find that the number of people making personal recommendations was only a few times greater than the number of people posting a public review on the website .
6-14:We observe that fiction books have relatively few recommendations compared to the number of reviews, while professional and technical books have more recommendations than reviews .
6-15:This could reflect several factors .
6-16:One is that people feel more confident reviewing fiction than technical books .
6-17:Another is that they hesitate to recommend a work of fiction before reading it themselves, since the recommendation must be made at the point of purchase .
6-18:Yet another explanation is that the median price of a work of fiction is lower than that of a technical book .
6-19:This means that the discount received for successfully recommending a mystery novel or thriller is lower and hence people have less incentive to send recommendations .
6-20:Next, we measure the per category efficacy of recommendations by observing the ratio of the number of purchases occurring within a week following a recommendation to the number of recommenders for each book subject category (column b of table 2) .
6-21:On average, only 2% of the recommenders of a book received a discount because their recommendation was accepted, and another 1% made a recommendation that resulted in a purchase, but not a discount .
6-22:We observe marked differences in the response to recommendation for different categories of books .
6-23:Fiction in general is not very effectively recommended, with only around 2% of recommenders succeeding .
6-24:The efficacy was a bit higher (around 3%) for non fiction books dealing with personal and leisure pursuits, but is significantly higher in the professional and technical category .
6-25:Medical books have nearly double the average rate of recommendation acceptance .
6-26:This could be in part attributed to the higher median price of medical books and technical books in general .
6-27:As we will see in Section 6, a higher product price increases the chance that a recommendation will be accepted .
6-28:Recommendations are also more likely to be accepted for certain religious categories: 4.3% for Christian living and theology and 4.8% for Bibles .
6-29:In contrast, books not tied to organized religions, such as ones on the subject of new age (2.5%) and occult (2.2%) spirituality, have lower recommendation effectiveness .
6-30:These results raise the interesting possibility that individuals have greater influence over one another in an organized context, for example through a professional contact or a religious one .
6-31:There are exceptions of course .
6-32:For example, Japanese anime DVDs have a strong following in the US, and this is reflected in their frequency and success in recommendations .
6-33:Another example is that of gardening .
6-34:In general, recommendations for books relating to gardening have only a modest chance of being accepted, which agrees with the individual prerogative that accompanies this hobby .
6-35:At the same time, orchid cultivation can be a highly organized and social activity, with frequent ‘shows" and online communities devoted entirely to orchids .
6-36:Perhaps because of this, the rate of acceptance of orchid book recommendations is twice as high as those for books on vegetable or tomato growing. .
